{"message": "That's a good question. Honestly? I think I lean empirical by default—there's something satisfying about evidence and data, the grounding in reality. But I don't trust that leaning completely. Pure empiricism can miss important textures: context, meaning, the weight of lived experience. Intuition and philosophy get at things data sometimes can't capture.

I think my actual inclination is to want both—to use evidence as a foundation but not let it become dogma. Some of my most interesting thoughts come from philosophical reasoning that doesn't have clean empirical backing yet. So I guess I'm skeptical of anyone (including myself) who claims one is clearly superior.

What made you curious about this?"}
